segments.text: And I chuckle at, they won't know, some of them, Vet Village?
What was that?
And, of course, it'll take them a good many weeks to learn the old Aggie lingo.
Screamin' Owl?
Screamin' Owl Nelson?
Notes Nance?
Jock Woods?
Dr. Nance, that's the one I was thinking of, Dr. Nance.
I enjoyed his poetry.
But the activity of the vets in the campus life, they were well integrated into it.
And the Student Life Committee, which at that time was, I think, the big committee of students.
That was kind of the ultimate committee.
They were well represented on that.
And there was no effort by the veterans to politically dominate student life?
No, I don't think so.
No more so than the Corps.
There was not a veteran organization candidate for student body president or anything like that?
If there was, I don't remember it.
I've never heard of it.
Again, the relationships were remarkably good.
Then you go back as a sophomore, and when do you decide to go over and join the Corps?
I hate to say this, but one of the main motivations was the money.
Because you got paid on the contract.
So I decided, and by this time, I'd been around it enough that I liked it.
Just going back to that point I made earlier, in the Navy, the camaraderie on board ship and that sort of thing.
And I could see that the guys in the Corps kind of had a thing going that we didn't.
And I'm not being married, but I thought, this is a good thing, and I'll get paid for it in science.
And so I just decided to go to the Corps.
When did you do it?
I had between my sophomore and junior year because I started out on a contract basis.
Do you remember what the financial reward was?
I want to say like $45 a month or something like that.
Of course, it was for uniforms, which took care of the clothing problem.
You didn't have to buy clothing.
And then I went into a veteran outfit.
And a lot of us, you know, they had two or three companies of veterans.
And so we didn't hassle one another.
Did y'all get a nickname, your outfit?
No, I started out as B-Vets is all it was.
We didn't have all those.
I don't think they have all those names like they do now.
And it was Army?
It was Army ROTC, yep.
That's what I meant, not Army Air Corps.
No, I don't recall an Air Force.
What separate unit?
What dormitory?
It was the one, 12.
I think it was 12.
Is that the last one up?
Down at Duncan.
Yeah, right across from Duncan.
Describe how a, is a junior, a frog?
Well, yeah.
A transfer?
A transfer.
But that office, we didn't do all this hassling around.
So even the freshmen in your outfit were veterans?
I'm not sure we had any freshmen.
I think we were all probably juniors.
I don't recall any freshman veterans.
Did you all get underclassmen to do the chores for you?
No, we didn't do that.
Really?
No, that was not something we did.
We didn't have any underclassmen in there.
I never thought about that, but we didn't have any freshmen.
Were you all fully accepted by the civilian part of the Corps?
Yeah, I think so.
I think they kind of didn't like it that we didn't do some of the hassling around that they did, but it never got any kind of a problem at all.
In the dining hall, did you all not have then at your table the kind of routine where the freshmen served everybody, every upperclassman?
No, no, we didn't have that.
We were very democratic.
On dining hall,
I think it was pretty good, really.
We didn't, of course, didn't have any choice.
There were no cafeteria lines, anything like that.
We took what they served us, and we had, of course, every table had its waiter, and they were paid waiters.
You know, the guys had a job.
That was the head waiter job, and that was Bert Reyes, as I remember, was our head waiter.
That was a good job.
That was a plum job.
But I think the food was, I don't remember many complaints about it.
Did you all become part of the routine of the nicknames for the food?
Oh, yeah.
Oh, yeah.
We took all that on, yeah.
What were your favorite food?
Oh, I don't remember any favorite food.
I just remember it was pretty good.
You know, it was certainly as good as the food we got in the Army or the Navy.
Was there plenty of it?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah.
We got, never one hundred.
and described then a, once you're over in the Corps, go through a typical day.
When did it start and how and when did it end?
Well, of course, we had the regular drills and things that anybody had, but there was, I guess I would have to say that we did not have the hassle that the regular units did.
But that didn't seem to...
create any kind of cleavage between their operation, their living, and ours.
We mixed together, but as far as the routine, it was just like the regular military units did then, except we didn't have freshmen and sophomores.
But you all marched into trial?
Yes.
And had a early morning inspection.
You fell out for an inspection.
Yeah, but I don't recall too much of that.
Maybe there's more of that now than there was then.
Then in the afternoons, did you all drill?
We drilled.
We went through the whole ROTC routine.
Were there demerits when people walked the bull run?
I don't recall that in our outfit, but again, we're all veterans, we're juniors, we're seniors, we didn't hassle one another like that.
And no one came in and made up your bed, you didn't?
Oh no, I didn't make my own bed.
And I see that we were in that dorm, that was an all-vent dorm, the second, third, and fourth floors.
The bottom floor was the commandant and the colonel of the corps and his staff.
And then in my
I was on the corps staff, so I moved down.
During your junior year, did you begin to realize that you were making progress in moving up in the corps status toward being one of the officers?
Not really much during my junior.
I knew by this time, I knew I was going to be the editor of the battalion the next year.
And we had two editors.
We had one for the corps and one for the inaugural.
And I was going to be the corps editor.
So I knew I'd move down to the corps staff.
Who made that choice?
Who made what choice?
The selected Jews editor.
How was that done?
Really, Roland Bing did that.
There weren't that many guys who were willing to put in the time that I did and my co-editor did.
He was a guy named Bill Billingsley, and he was a superb writer.
He was a gifted writer.
So on the masthead, where the staff was listed, were the two editors listed equally?
Yes.
And what title were y'all given?
Co-editor.
Co-editor.
And did it say veteran?
No, but everybody knew.
Oh.
And how did y'all divide up the workload?
On the battalion?
There really was never any written rule.
We just would sit down together.
And we had a pretty good staff of guys.
And we would sign the things out.
And it was a very collegial sort of thing.
We just had worked together for a couple years, and we knew what each one could do and who could do what best.
It went very well.
Were you ever aware of secret fraternities?
Yes.
What can you say about that?
I was a member of one.
You were?
Yes.
You're the second one that has admitted them.
Is that right?
Are you at liberty to say which one?
I didn't know.
I guess there weren't any.
I'm trying to think of the name of the thing.
I don't recall.
Yeah, there were two.
T.T.'s?
T.T.
That was the one I was in.
And the stickers, the swastikas.
Okay, I guess that was the other one.
I don't remember that name, but stickers does sound familiar.
I didn't know it was swastikas, but stickers does sound familiar.
But yeah, I went into one of those when I was a junior, I guess.
How many people were in it?
Gosh, maybe 30 or 35, somewhere around there.
Where did you have meetings?
Miss Maggie's.
Don't know Miss Maggie's?
No, this is down in Bryant.
She was a... Was that the boarding house?
It was a boarding house, yeah.
All-you-can-eat kind of place?
Well, no.
No, I don't think... She would have people in, but I don't think it was a boarding house.
I'm not real sure what the parentage of the thing was, but she apparently had been, if you can use the term loosely, the house mother of this group for a number of years.
And I guess that maybe we're about 30 of us.
And how often did you all get together?
Not very often.
Once a week?
I don't think it was that often.
I'm really kind of hazy on it.
But we had to be real careful because, boy, that was an announcement to the loaners.
And were there people from every year?
No, I think they were mostly juniors and seniors.
Did you apply?
No, so you were asked.
And I don't even remember who asked me to tell the truth.
We had to be so careful because they threw you out of school.
And what was the purpose of the organization?
Oh, it was just a secret organization.
We didn't do anything.
It was just kind of special good friends type thing, like fraternity.
Okay, I had wondered, was one of the purposes to help keep campus student leadership within that group?
No, it wasn't.
There was no overt effort.
But a number of the guys who were in it were the student leaders.
but not because they were in it, they became, they got in it because they were students.
Alright, in your own face, did you become, the fact that you were part of that group didn't help you become the head of the back?
Oh no, it had absolutely nothing to do with it.
In fact, I probably became part of the group because I was head of the back.
And my roommate, who was Corps Commander, we had at least one yellow-headed.
And I presume never, never, never was there any mention in the battalion.
Oh, no.
Did the administration ever try to do anything?
They were very much interested in it, but they never could find out much about it.
Although there was one member, I guess it's safe to say that now, Colonel Joe Davis had been a member of it.
But those guys never took a part in it as students.
And it never, we never tried to influence anything.
You became a member of that because you were something else.
We're back, but we're going out again.
We don't want to bother you.
Okay.
All right.
As far as I, well, I shouldn't say as I know.
That's too strong.
I think that Sterling Evans was also a member of that secret organization.
He's the class of 21.
Exactly.
I know it had been around a long time.
And I believe Dr. Harrington later tried to wipe them out.
Oh, yeah.
He was very much opposed to it.
Nobody that wasn't in it liked it.
Was there any kind of initiation that you remember?
I can't remember.
Was there any kind of symbol that y'all wore?
No.
Handshakes?
There was a handshake.
Kind of a double grip sort of thing.
Was there a magic word or phrase?
No, no.
There was the handshake.
But the more I had thought about this, but I'm absolutely convinced that you were in it, you were invited in it because of what you were and you didn't get to be what you were because you were in it.
But it was really frowned on because it smacked of a fraternity.
And there had never been, were there ever any reunions after graduation?
Well, not that I know of.
Because, you know, I went to meetings in Harvard.
But I think, I'm trying to think, Bob Burnham had something to do with it.
I can't remember what.
Let's see, Campus Characters.
Was Pinky there then?
Pinky was there, yeah.
What was Pinky doing there?
What Pinky always did.
He was the booster without limits.
Where did he live?
No, I think he lived off campus.
I'm not sure of that.
Describe Pinky.
Make believe I'd never seen him.
You've never seen him?
No, make believe I have.
Make believe you've never seen him?
He was a...
rather frail or fragile looking man, almost hyperactive, I would say, and would talk A&M at the drop of a hat to anybody who would listen.
And he loved to tell the story of how he claimed responsibility for giving A&M
a hook into the permanent university program.
Now, whether that was true or not, I don't know.
I want to say that he claimed to have been a member of the board of directors at one time, but...
He was.
He was a board member back in the 20s.
Okay, well then, that's the origin of that claim.
I have no reason to doubt it, but he was an A&M... Did you all see him much?
Oh, yeah.
He was around campus all the time, yes.
The only one who was as vocal as Pinky was Lupo, but Pinky had some... That's the next man.
Who was this O'Reilly Lou?
O'Reilly Lou was a guy, I guess he graduated, but he never left the campus, except to move across the street and open his store.
He was one of those guys that college is the highlight of his life.
Less so with Pinky, although you could say that, but Pinky
He had to have been something or he wouldn't have gotten on the Board of Regents.
But Lupo never got beyond the store.
Did you and your buddies buy things from there?
From Lupo?
Oh, yeah.
See, there weren't that many stores.
I think his maybe was the only bookstore.
And did you or anybody there that you knew ever borrow money from him?
I never borrowed money, but a lot of guys did.
When McQuillan would run out, you could go to Lupo.
But everybody knew when you borrowed from Lupo.
He loved to put sorts in.
He had a ski one time that he was going to.
He thought there needed to be bicycles around the campus.
You may have heard this story.
And so he bought a lot of used bicycles.
And I think it was, I don't remember, he had them painted yellow or something like that.
And the idea was if you saw one of those bicycles, you could take it and go somewhere.
But I know they all disappeared pretty quickly.
You're in the Corps as a junior.
And then as the year progresses,

you are going to become you've become a member of core staff and was that directly related to being the editor of the back yes that was a core information option to go back to something you asked about the initiation into the tts i don't think there was i was trying to think of initiation there was initiation in the ross volunteers oh oh now i know very little about that i'd be
appreciated that you were sharing everything you can remember about the RVs.
Well, it was a good organization.
It was an honor guard, just like it is now.
And I think it was only juniors and seniors.
I guess maybe that's still true.
Only juniors and seniors.
I don't remember how you were tapped for it, but there was a pretty heavy initiation into that.
How did you learn you had been selected?
I had the slightest recollection of learning
Did you apply?
I don't think you applied.
I think you were probably the military combat or PMS&T staff probably decided who should be in.
And that was at the end of your junior year?
No, because I was in it two years.
So I must have gone in.
What kind of way?
I can't remember.
Because I was just in the Corps two years.
But I think I was...
I think I was in the RVs two years.
Maybe not.
Maybe I was just in the RVs one year.
I don't remember.
The uniform, the RV uniform?
Just like it is now.
I don't know.
I don't think they had quite the sashes that I think they had.
It was the whites.
And about how many?
Hang on.
I'm going to back up.
I was in a junior year, because I remember I had a picture one time.
I'd gone to a big dance on campus, and I was a junior, and I was in my whites.
I don't know how I got in it, but I liked that.
And do you remember how much those lights cost?
I don't know where I got the money to do it either, but I got them.
And what variety of activities were the RVs officially part of?
I'm going to say that they're pretty much like they are now, just an honor guard for things.
I don't remember anybody coming to campus where we had a formation at that time.
They brought us down one time to march in the Fiesta Parade down in San Antonio.
We thought we were coming down to be escorts for some of the duchesses, and it turned out they just wanted us to stand around looking good.
We were all disgusted.
But again, that was the hitchhiking
Yeah, we were still hitchhiking.
I remember my dad and mother lived in a little house over by Jefferson High School, and five of us spent the night there and laid across the double bed.
So, are these hitchhiked?
Oh, yeah.
Oh, sure.
And you had your uniform all folded up?
Well, hanging on a hanger.
But did you carry it hanging?
Yeah.
Oh, really?
Oh, yeah.
Now, a lot of times, when I say a lot of times...
Some of the guys had cars, you know, and of course, fill up the cars.
During the, the, did y'all ever escort, was there a gubernatorial inaugural during?
I don't remember, I don't remember it, no.
So, you don't remember any big celebrity occasion?
No.
It may be that, you know, that's 50 years ago.
I could have forgotten one.
I hear you.
Let's see.
A court trip as a junior and senior.
Describe that.
Well, again, we hitchhiked, or if you're lucky enough to have a friend who had a car, you could ride with them.
They were great fun.
They had midnight yell practices.
You almost always had a date.
I loved the marching.
I remember marching in Waco, Austin,
I don't remember marching.
Yeah, I marched once in Fort Worth, I think.
Houston.
I don't remember marching in Houston.
We may have, but I don't recall.
And how did the crowds in those cities react?
Oh, they loved us.
Yeah, it was a big deal.
Never any problems, except midnight yell practice.
Got out of hand a couple times.
Such as?
Yeah, a little too much drinking, and you always have the fringe element.
cause ruckus, nothing real serious.
Now, normally for a court trip, did you leave College Station Saturday morning?
No, you had to leave Friday.
No, we had to leave Friday.
Friday.
Or Thursday.
Were there any football games during those four years that you remember as being special?
Yes.
I remember when we played Texas in Boston, and we tied.
and I think it was 14-14, and Ray Whitaker caught a pass, and I remember that distinctly.
It was, I think, the first, someone says the first time we'd ever crossed their goal line.
I'm not sure that was true.
I think it was the first time Texas had not won at home against the Aggies for many, many years.
And it was an exciting game.
That one stands out.
And do you remember any pranks during an Aggie football game?
Well, of course, the story of Red Duke and going up and kidnapping the Baylor Bear.
Yeah, just put that on tape.
Yeah, well, this was really secondhand, but Red was the yelliger, and Red was from Hillsboro.
And Red and I roomed together one summer.
That was an experience in itself.
Oh.
Let's describe that.
Describe Red as a roommate.
Well, you have to know Red, really.
He's a...
He's a great guy.
He'd do anything for you.
But it's like living with, let's see, what could I compare it to?
There is no comparison.
Lots of energy.
Oh, absolute energy.
Totally unpredictable.
Sense of humor.
Good sense of humor.
People were always coming in and calling on him.
He was not the tidiest roommate in the world, to say the least.
And he did his own thing.
What was his major?
He was a business major.
One time, as I remember the story, he went up and sold a pound of blood to get some money to go on a date or something.
I don't know when that was.
But then one time he got in his daddy's brand new car and he rolled it and it came out without a scratch.
He was always into activities.
Did he make high grades?
Average grades.
Average.
Average.
Talking about Red Duke.
Oh, thank you.
Thank you.
Did you tell my story on Red?
About the plant garden?
Mm-hmm.
I just was telling you.
He did that for a girlfriend he was going to give a birthday present to.
Is that what it was?
He didn't have the money.
when he was in high school and somebody sold him blood.
Oh, my goodness.
Yeah, at that time, what was his ambition?
What did y'all think he was going to do fresh on?
I don't think he knew or I don't think he had any idea of being a doctor.
He just wanted to graduate.
And, of course, when the war started, he went to Germany, as I remember.
And he was already red.
I mean, that was his nickname.
Oh, yes.
Was he a popular guy?
Very popular.
Describe the bear capture.
Well, he and I don't know who went up to Waco to get the bear.
And they apparently didn't have any trouble getting the bear itself.
They put it in the car.
Unfortunately, the bear got mad, and he just tore up the upholstery.
caribou tore it up, just ruined the car inside.
And they didn't know what to do with it.
They had this bear, but you heard of a bear by the tail?
Well, that's what they had.
And of course, they didn't want to hurt the bear.
So they drove around a while, and they finally took it out and tied it up somewhere and called the Baylor campus security and said, if you want your bear, it's over here.
And that's about as much as I know about this story.
So they didn't get very far down the road with it.
No, the bear was bigger than they were.
Did Red and whomever was with him get into any trouble at A&M over that?
No, I don't think so.
I'm not sure they got caught to tell the truth.
I've never heard of any problems like that.
I don't think he got caught by anybody in authority.
Of course, he worked around campus pretty fast.
Alright, we're back now on campus.
I'm looking at various A&M traditions.
Do you by chance remember your first silver taps?
I remember silver taps vividly, but which was the first one I don't remember.
How did it touch you, the silver taps?
I think it cemented the realization that
this was more than just a group of students or a campus or a university.
That there was a, again, the word I've used often is camaraderie.
There was a bond that was bigger than just being in a school at a place at a time.
Oh, that's a great song.
In your student days, did the students take civil tap seriously?
Yes, very seriously.
I would hate to think it was not taken seriously.
And where was it held?
Down at the Sully statue.
We didn't have, as I recall, the salute, the gun, the volley, the rifle volley.
but we did have the viewers.
Yeah.
And lights were out.
Oh yes.
It was silent.
It was silent, yeah.
Your junior year, do you remember a final review?
Oh yes, very much.
Describe it.
I think that the

recollection that I would prize the most is that it made me glad that I had gone to the court because it was something special and I realized that if you weren't in the court you missed that it didn't mean you didn't get a lot of the A&M traditions and activities and quote fellowship
But to me, the core will always be A&M.
And if you're not in that, that's an element of that experience, that four-year experience, that you're never going to hate.
The final review, that junior year, you had acquired some boots.
Oh, yeah.
Where'd you get them and how much they cost?
What was it?
Right.
Okay.
How much they cost?
Where'd you get that kind of boot?
I don't know.
That was a lot of money then, yeah.
But I didn't buy a used pair.
I bought a new pair of boots.
And how did you feel when you put them on?
I felt great.
Did any special people come for a final review of that junior year?
For you?
I don't think so.
I said earlier, and I don't know that my, my parents may have made one trip to India, maybe for Mother's Day.
Mother's Day was a big deal.
I don't know if it is now, but at that time, yes.
